{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643038"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:48:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:48:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17980"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17980"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73083"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58554"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"8122"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73083"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements is true regarding the excretion of water-soluble products of xenobiotic metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They are easily excreted in urine","They accumulate in adipose tissue","They are metabolised to lipid-soluble products for excretion","They are excreted primarily through the lungs","They require active transport for excretion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWater-soluble products of xenobiotic metabolism are \u003Cstrong\u003Eeasily excreted in urine\u003C/strong\u003E because they can be filtered by the kidneys and eliminated from the body. This is in contrast to lipid-soluble compounds, which often require further metabolism to become water-soluble before they can be excreted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey accumulate in adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - Water-soluble compounds do not typically accumulate in fat\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey are metabolised to lipid-soluble products for excretion\u003C/strong\u003E - The opposite is true; lipid-soluble compounds are metabolised to water-soluble forms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey are excreted primarily through the lungs\u003C/strong\u003E - The lungs are not a major route for excretion of water-soluble compounds\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey require active transport for excretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Water-soluble compounds are usually excreted passively through the kidneys\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Water-soluble metabolites of xenobiotics are typically excreted more easily than lipid-soluble ones.","Water-soluble compounds are primarily excreted through the kidneys into the urine.","Lipid-soluble compounds often require further metabolism to become water-soluble before excretion."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski C